sec.p:
In order to unravel the possible origin of the better performance after P/W co-doping, the DFT calculations are then applied for both HER and HzOR. Combined with the theoretical calculation and the experimental result regarding the structural stability after doping, it is reasonable to use the model where the surface Co atoms in Co3N are replaced by W atoms and subsurface N atoms are replaced by P atoms, as indicated in Fig. 8a–d, Supplementary Fig. 26 and Supplementary Note 2. It has been generally demonstrated that the HER process can be described with three states including an initial pair of H+ and e-, an intermediate of adsorbed H (H*) and the final product of 1/2 H2, as shown in Fig. 8e. As the critical descriptor, the free energy of hydrogen absorption (∆GH*) of PW-Co3N is calculated to be −0.41 eV, which is closer to the thermoneutral value than that of the pure Co3N (−0.52 eV). This could imply the facilitated hydrogen adsorption/desorption behavior upon P/W doping59,60, which is consistent with better HER activity of PW-Co3N NWA/NF. In order to understand the fact that the ∆GH* of PW-Co3N is far more negative compared to benchmark Pt (−0.10 eV) while their HER catalytic activity is almost the same, we further conducted DFT calculations on d-band center analysis, the water absorption energy ΔEH2O\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
